Exponential Coalescent Analyses

Nicola Mueller

2020-02-03

1 Summary

  • There is signal to estimate evolutionary rates in the data based on date randomization tests.
  • The evolutionary rate of novel Coronavirus is estimated to be most likely somewhere between 1x10-3 and 2x10-3.
  • The tMRCA is quite uncertain, but is inferred to most likely around the beginning of December using a constant coalescent and mid December using en exponential coalescent model.

1.1 Estimating the evolutionary rate of novel Coronavirus

I here estimate the evolutionary rate of novel Coronavirus using different priors on the exponential growth rate. This is done with the same sequences as in https://nextstrain.org/ncov, analysing the data in BEAST2(Bouckaert et al. 2014). I used a strict clock model and an HKY + Gamma4 site model, treating every site the same. The clock rate is assumed to be lognormal distributed with m=0 and s=4. Additionally, I only used the sites 1000-29000 from the aligned sequence file. For the exponential coalescent, I’ve used a normal distribution around 0 and sigma=100. The final Ne (resp. just the Ne in the constant coalescent case) is assumed to be lognormal distribution with m=0 and s=2. I compare these rate estimates when using the true dates (results in blue) of each sample and then compare it to the estimates when randomizing the tip dates(Duchêne et al. 2015). Randomizing the tip dates essentially removes the time information from the sequence data and therefore removes the possibility to correctly estimate these rates. This randomization is done 10 times and the results are shown in orange. This therefore tells us how much information about the evolutionary rates there is in the data in absence of the population prior. In the plots, the outer bars approx. correspond to 95% intervals.

expo_dat$x_offset = 1
expo_dat[which(expo_dat$dates=="true"), "x_offset"] = 0

p_evol = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$masking==0), ]) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y=clockRate, x=x_offset+date_rep, group=interaction(dates,date_rep), color=dates),outlier.shape = NA) +
  xlab("")+
  ylab("evolutionary rate per site and year")+
  scale_x_continuous(labels=c())+
  facet_wrap(~growth_prior, ncol=2) +
  scale_y_log10()+
  scale_color_OkabeIto()+
  theme_minimal()+
  ggtitle("Evolutionary rates estimates using coalescent models\nwith different priors")
plot(p_evol)

ggsave(file="figures/clock_rates.pdf", height=4, width=8)

1.2 Time of the most recent common ancestor using the coalescent with exponential growth

For all the scenarios where I used the true sampling dates, I also estimated the time of the most recent common ancestor of all sequences.

When assuming a constant population over time (constant coalescent), the tMRCA is inferred to be most likely at the beginning of December, while an exponentially growing population puts the tMRCA most likely somewhere mid December, but does not exlcude the beginning of December.

p_tmrca = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$masking==0 & expo_dat$dates=="true"), ]) +
  geom_density(aes(x=mrca, group=growth_prior, color=growth_prior)) +
  xlab("")+
  scale_x_date(limits=as.Date(c("2019-10-01", "2020-01-01")))+
  ggtitle("Time of the most recent common ancestor") +
  scale_color_OkabeIto(name=("population model"))+
  theme_minimal()
ggsave(file="figures/beast_coal-tmrca_20200130.png", height=3.5, width=5)
plot(p_tmrca)

1.3 What is the tMRCA

The time of the most recent common ancestor (or tMRCA), denotes the time when all the sequenced cases in a dataset last shared a common ancestor. It does not, for example, denote when a virus first entered the human population. In fact, the earliest time possible of the MRCA is the time of the zoonosis, if all sequenced cases are from the human population and zoonosis occured only once.

Example phylogeny where the time of the initial zoonosis is different from the most recent common ancestor of several sequenced cases

1.4 Do the models fit the observed tree?

In order to test if the constant and exponential coalescent fit the obeserved tree patterns, I next sampled phylogenetic trees under the prior, using the two coalescent models. The idea is that if the model used is a good description of what actually happends, then the trees generated under this model with the estimated parameters from the data should lead to similarly looking trees(Duchene et al. 2019). I used the distribution of estimated effective population sizes and growth rates as an “empirical” distribution of these parameters. This means that I essentially fixed these two parameters to be always a random sample from the two estimated distribution of these paramters. When comparing the estimated tree heights and lengths to the predicted ones, the exponential coalescent is a better description of what happens than the constant coalescent. However, under both boths, with the inferred parameters, the roots are expected to be further in the past than they actually are expected to be slightly longer than they are in reality, showing that either model doesn’t perfectly describe the observed patterns

expo_nomask = expo_dat[which(expo_dat$masking==0 & expo_dat$dates=="true"), c("Tree.height", "Tree.treeLength", "growth_prior")]
expo_nomask$approach = "estimated"


t = read.table(paste(path, "predicted/expo_1_true_1_1_rep1.predicted.log", sep="/"), sep="\t", header=T)
t=t[,c("Tree.height", "Tree.treeLength")]
t = t[-seq(1,length(t$Sample)/10),]
t$growth_prior = "constant coalescent"
t$approach = "predicted"
expo_nomask = rbind(expo_nomask, t)

t = read.table(paste(path, "predicted/expo_2_true_1_1_rep1.predicted.log", sep="/"), sep="\t", header=T)
t=t[,c("Tree.height", "Tree.treeLength")]
t = t[-seq(1,length(t$Sample)/10),]
t$growth_prior = "exponential coalescent"
t$approach = "predicted"
expo_nomask = rbind(expo_nomask, t)

p_height= ggplot(expo_nomask) +
  geom_density(aes(x=Tree.height, group = interaction(growth_prior, approach), fill=approach), alpha=0.5) +
  xlab("")+
  facet_wrap(.~growth_prior, scales="free_x")+
  ggtitle("Tree height") +
  theme_minimal()
p_length = ggplot(expo_nomask) +
  geom_density(aes(x=Tree.treeLength, group = interaction(growth_prior, approach), fill=approach), alpha=0.5) +
  xlab("")+
  facet_wrap(.~growth_prior, scales="free_x")+
  ggtitle("Tree length") +
  theme_minimal()

require(grid)
require(gridExtra)

grid.arrange(p_height, p_length)

1.5 Estimating the evolutionary rate of novel Coronavirus when allowing for base calling errors

To see what happens when we allow for errors in the consensus calls, I next randomly ignore SNPs that only occured once in the entire alignment of sequences. This is done at a probability of 0.25 and repeated 10 times. This means that every SNP that only occured once in the entire alignment has a probability of 0.25 to be replaced by an ‘N’ (i.e. could have been any base). In all repetitions and for both population models, the evolutionary rate is estimated to be most likely above 10^-3, but is overall very uncertain.

expo_dat$x_offset = 10
expo_dat[which(expo_dat$dates=="true"), "x_offset"] = 0

p_evol = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$masking==0.25), ]) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y=clockRate, x=x_offset+date_rep+masking_rep, group=interaction(dates,date_rep,masking_rep)),outlier.shape = NA) +
  xlab("")+
  ylab("evolutionary rate per site and year")+
  scale_x_continuous(labels=c())+
  facet_wrap(~growth_prior, ncol=2) +
    scale_y_log10()+
  theme_minimal()+
  ggtitle("Evolutionary rates estimates masking single mutations at a probability of 0.25")
plot(p_evol)

1.6 tMRCA estimate when masking random nucleotides

When assuming that some of the mutations that only occured once in the alignment are due to false consensus calls, the inferred time of the most recent common ancestor is moved closer to mid December. The different curves denote different probability densities of the tMRCA for different random masking iterations.

p_tmrca = ggplot(expo_dat[which( expo_dat$dates=="true" & expo_dat$masking==0.25), ]) +
  geom_density(aes(x=mrca, group=interaction(masking_rep,growth_prior)),outlier.shape = NA) +
  xlab("")+
  scale_x_date(limits=as.Date(c("2019-10-01", "2020-01-01")))+
  facet_wrap(~growth_prior, ncol=2, scale="free_y")+
  ggtitle("Time of the most recent common ancestor\nmasking single mutations at a probability of 0.25") +
  theme_minimal()
plot(p_tmrca)

1.7 growth rate estimates

For the exponential coalescent, we estimate growth rates, as well as the final effective population size. There are a lot of assumptions that go into this values, such as that all samples in the population are random draws from a well mixed population. Additionally, this assumes that there is no super spreading or populations structure. These results should therefore be treating with caution.

The R0 is computed from the the growth rate using different average duration of infectiousness and the inferred growth rates for the exponential coalescent. The computation of the R0 is based on the equation and here, assuming becoming uninfectious is exponentially distributed with average duration of infectiousness=1/becoming uninfectious rate.

p_growth = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$dates=="true" & expo_dat$growth_prior=="exponential coalescent" & expo_dat$masking==0), ]) +
  geom_density(aes(x=growthRate)) +
  xlab("")+
  facet_wrap(~masking, ncol=2) +
  ggtitle("Estimates of the growth rates") +
  xlab("growth rate")+
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#999999','#E69F00', '#56B4E9'), name="average infectious period in days")

p_doubling = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$dates=="true" & expo_dat$growth_prior=="exponential coalescent" & expo_dat$masking==0), ]) +
  geom_density(aes(x=log(2)/growthRate*365)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-2,25))+
  xlab("")+
  facet_wrap(~masking, ncol=2) +
  ggtitle("Estimates of the doubling times") +
  xlab("double time")+
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#999999','#E69F00', '#56B4E9'), name="average infectious period in days")


# compute the R0 for different becoming uninfectious rates
average_infectious = c(15, 10, 5)

becomin_uninfectious = 1/average_infectious*365

expo_dat$R0 = 1+expo_dat$growthRate/36.5


p_R0 = ggplot(expo_dat[which(expo_dat$dates=="true" & expo_dat$growth_prior=="exponential coalescent" & expo_dat$masking==0), ]) +
  geom_density(aes(x=(1+growthRate/becomin_uninfectious[[1]]), color=factor(average_infectious[1]))) +
  geom_density(aes(x=(1+growthRate/becomin_uninfectious[[2]]), color=factor(average_infectious[2]))) +
  geom_density(aes(x=(1+growthRate/becomin_uninfectious[[3]]), color=factor(average_infectious[3]))) +
  xlab("")+
  facet_wrap(~masking, ncol=2) +
  ggtitle("Estimate of R0 for different becoming uninfectious rates") +
  xlab("R0")+
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#999999','#E69F00', '#56B4E9'), name="average infectious period in days")

require(grid)
require(gridExtra)

lay <- rbind(c(1,2),
             c(3))

grid.arrange(p_growth, p_doubling, p_R0, ncol=2, layout_matrix = lay)
